Ending a deception can be hard because people might feel lonely. They might not want to talk to you anymore. The problem is even harder when the deception is about gender. Why does someone feel they must be someone they are not? In Viola's case, she pretends to be a man to stay safe in a new country. Her plan works, but she also feels alone. She does not fit in with the women around her. Olivia loves Cesario, who is actually Viola. She also wants Viola/Cesario to love her. But Viola does not want to love Olivia. This is hard for Viola. The play shows that deception can help people discover their feelings. For example, Olivia might really love women, not men. However, the play might also show that people judge others only by their looks.

German colonial rule, many people say, was cruel. This is especially true about the victims of the Ovaherero and Nama people in German South West Africa. But, Germany's colonial empire was different in many ways. It had different policies and ruling styles. Education in colonies was also different. In East Africa, the German government had many schools. People said this was good. But in South West Africa, the situation was different. The German government did not have many schools for the local people. Missionaries did this. But, they had few resources. In South West Africa, the German government did not support the local people. They supported the European people more. This had long effects on South West Africa. Many local people were not educated. Other German colonies had more educated local people. This paper talks about why this was different in South West Africa. It looks at new research on settlers and colonial authorities and their attitudes towards local people.
There is much writing about education in the German colonial empire. Most of this writing is in German. It was written in the early twentieth century. These early writings talked about how the education system worked in each colony. Later writings in English compared education in different colonies. They also looked at different parts of education. Cohen's study looked at education in South West Africa and East Africa. Cohen said the large settler population in South West Africa affected the education system.
South West Africa was not as hot as other German colonies. Many Europeans lived there. By 1913, there were 15,000 Europeans. This was more than East Africa, which had 5,336 Europeans.

People have made many types of popular music in the last 100 years. Some types, like rap, rock, country, jazz, and folk, have many small types and even smaller small types. One of these small types is called Heavy Metal rock. It is very different from other music. It has many feelings, always on the dark side. People started making their own small types of Heavy Metal rock very quickly. Now, there are many types of Heavy Metal rock. People think it is a big group with many styles. It started with one song, "Helter Skelter," by the Beatles. They wanted to show they could be as loud and heavy as the Rolling Stones.

Metal music is very loud and strong. People who play it know how to play their instruments well. Some metal music is also about drugs. People in the 1970s used drugs to make music that was different and surprising. Many songs have dark and scary words. Later, people used these dark words to make new metal music. It is a big group with many styles, but it started with one song.

Henri Rousseau, a famous Post-Impressionist artist, painted The Dream. This painting shows a woman in a dream. It also shows Rousseau's own dreams and goals. Rousseau wanted to be accepted and praised by artists and art lovers. He had a choice: follow styles others liked or be unique and independent. The Dream shows his struggle to decide.

Before understanding The Dream, know Rousseau's story. He was born on May 21, 1844, in Laval, France. His father was a tinsmith. Rousseau did not train in art. He worked for France until age 40. His wife and eight children died. He turned to painting for comfort.

Rousseau's desire for acceptance is understandable. He began later than other artists. He wanted to be admired, like Matisse. However, he had to choose between following styles or being unique.

Many smart people think that ethics and beauty are closely connected. They believe this because truth and beauty are the same thing. We learn about ethics and beauty through education or experience. However, we often appreciate them without being taught. Both ethics and beauty tell us what is good or beautiful, not how to make good art or moral choices. Even if we discuss art or morals, we cannot fully explain why something is good or beautiful. A conversation about Da Vinci's Mona Lisa may talk about foreground, background, and cultural context, but it cannot fully explain why it is good art. People often say, "There's just something about it" when asked about their favorite art or literature. Ethics has the same problem. No matter how well we describe a work, there is always more to it. I think this "something" is the most important part of both ethics and art. It makes them powerful and connects them. We feel ethics and art strongly at a deep level, but we cannot fully explain it. This is especially true for literature. McKean says that literature is unique because it has a strong moral quality. It is important to us because it has values like our lives do.

Germany today is strong and united. It has its own culture from the Alps in Munich to the Baltic Sea in Kiel. The same culture is felt from Cologne on the Rhine, through the middle of Germany to Dresden on the Elbe. With this unique culture, it is not surprising that Germany is made up of different tribes and sources.

Germania is the ancient land of the Germans. The name's origin is debated. Tacitus said it comes from the Tungrian Tribe. Caesar used "Germanus" to distinguish between conquered Gauls and non-conquered Germans. Others say it comes from the Old Irish word for "shout", meaning Germans were loud.

Tacitus, in his AD 98 book, said Germans were not mixed with other races. They lived on the Roman Empire's borders and traded goods and skills. They served in the Roman army.

I looked at a bowl of fruit. My mind was not thinking about it. It just looked at the picture. A book told me to think about things differently. It said to look at a picture and put a frame around it. This makes the picture easy to see. I tried this, but I was too surprised. Some people leave things in the toilet. I could not move it. I tried to clean it, but it was stuck. I had to think about it more. I will try again.

Teenagers often die in car crashes. This happens because of many reasons. The National Institutes of Health says the teen brain is not ready for driving. They also lack driving experience. This causes more accidents. When teens drive with friends, they have more accidents. A study in California shows this. Some states give teens temporary licenses with limits. But these are not enough. The teen brain is not good at driving. A psychologist says 18 is too young for a driver's license. USA Today reports that teens want to take risks. We should delay driving until this stops. If we do not, more teens will die. By 2010, many new teen drivers will be on the road. Schools can teach driving, but no one under 18 can drive. A provisional permit can be given before a full license. A certain number of training hours should be required. This can be the same as in other states. The problem affects all states. So, national laws can help. This is not a new idea.

I looked at many old Edison films at the Library of Congress. I saw fifteen trick films made between 1895 and 1901. These films use clever editing to create tricks. I studied these films to describe how they worked and how some of the later films were different.

Most trick films from that time were made on a stage with no camera movement. They used long and medium shots, never close-ups. This style comes from theatre and magic acts. Actors mostly moved side-to-side and did not walk towards or away from the camera. For example, in "Uncle Josh in a Spooky Hotel" (1900), actors move from right to left along the stage. The camera does not follow them.

Trick films usually had one main idea per film. This made them short, about one minute or less. They did not have much story; they focused on tricks like magic or disappearing acts. But sometimes, a trick film used many shots together to make one illusion. For example, in "The Execution of Mary, Queen of Scots" (1895), the film seems like one shot, but it is made from many shots joined together.

John Taylor of Caroline was early and strong supporter of Republicanism. He was farmer first but also had short time in politics. This made him well-known for his strong views on personal freedom and government. His love for farming was main reason for his views on government. He wanted to keep and grow best jobs.

Taylor thought United States had good chance to make best system because no old tradition to stop it. He believed in natural rights of people. He said if one right is taken, all others are weak. These rights should not be controlled by government. He said in nature, people with power and bad ideas get ahead, but in society, this should not happen.

To make best society, Taylor said government should accept good and bad in people. He believed in dualistic morality, or two sides of good and bad. He said good government should protect property, help farming, and stop capitalism. Even bad leaders can make good government work, he thought. They just need watch to keep out bad ideas.

Taylor wanted strict rules for the Constitution. He wanted small Federal government with only the powers written in Constitution. He knew big government could be bad and expensive. But he also thought strict rules without understanding could be corrupt. He said the Declaration of Independence was real charter of United States, showing it as group of states, not one country.

There was a big drop in commuter logs in third month. It was a bit sad and we do not know why. Winter and busy school work may have caused this. December is busy time with holiday season. People do not need to come to campus. Classes start late in January. Maybe the project lost some energy. We made Carpool Challenge Week in March to help. People like driving cars. We gave out prizes for trying alternative ways. It would have been good to give bigger prizes. We might have seen more people join. But we did not change the prizes. Maybe bigger prizes would have helped.

An ETF is a security that tracks an index, commodity, or group of assets. It trades like a stock on an exchange. ETFs offer diversification, like index funds, and benefits of single stock ownership, such as short selling, buying on margin, and buying as few as one share. ETFs have low expense ratios compared to mutual funds. However, ETFs charge a commission for trades. Many types of ETFs are available.

It's important for investors to check if stated benefits exist. For this example, let's look at ETF IHF and its top 10 holdings. These holdings make up 63.58% of the ETF's assets. Here are the top 10 holdings and their percentages.

To see how well these stocks represent the ETF, we calculate the Beta and Return. These calculations are in the chart below.

The chart shows that a portfolio of just the top 10 holdings could give a higher return (6.11%) and a lower Beta (.12) than the ETF. However, these results might not be statistically different.

To check if the portfolios are different, we calculate the standard deviation of each top 10 stock and compare it to the ETF IHF.

Edgar Allan Poe's "Dream-Land" is a great poem. In it, he uses the word "Thulé." This word comes from Virgil's work, but another writer, Goethe, also used it. Poe might have learned this word from Goethe's poem "The King of Thulé." This poem is about a king who loses his wife and then himself. The king in Poe's poem is also lonely. He wants to die. Poe uses "Thulé" in his poem "The Pit and the Pendulum" too. "Dream-Land" and "The King of Thulé" are similar. In both, the speaker is lonely and sad. Poe might have been copying Goethe's poem. Poe also knew Goethe because he liked Tennyson. Tennyson said he admired Goethe. So, Poe likely read Goethe's work.

A judge will not quickly dismiss Jennifer Palmer’s claim for punitive damages. A judge must decide whether the defendant’s actions were done with bad intent or were very wrong. Palmer can show the manager, Paul Martin, should have known harm was likely by knowing about past slip-and-fall accidents. Palmer can also say Martin’s actions were bad because many accidents happened and Martin did not fix the problem. Palmer’s claim that Martin’s actions were bad is weak but reasonable.

On October 13, 2009, Rich Wayne told his manager, Paul Martin, about an applesauce spill. Martin said he was eating dinner and did not want to clean it. Later, another employee, Mary J. Haddigan, also told Martin about the spill, and he still did not clean it. At 5:30 pm, Jennifer Palmer slipped and fell on the spill and was hurt. Before Palmer’s accident, five slip-and-fall accidents had happened at D&D’s in 2009. Now, Palmer is suing for damages, and we are thinking about filing a motion to stop the punitive damages claim.

In California, a person can get punitive damages for not following a duty that is not in a contract. This can happen if the person acted with “oppression, fraud, or malice.” If the person did not want to cause harm, but still did something bad, it is still considered malicious. A judge will think the person acted with malice if they knew the harm could happen and did not try to stop it.

Four years ago, I took a class about Islam at CBC. We talked about if Islam is a dangerous religion. This question is still important today. After 9/11, American media went from being against Islam to being very nice. We couldn’t have a Muslim president in 2001.

The Prophet Muhammad’s story is interesting. The history says he was a humble prophet. But I thought he forced people to become Muslim. He fought to conquer tribes and made them follow Islam. But the story says he was misunderstood and people came to him on their own.

Muhammad’s miracles are like Jesus’s. Once he took food and made more than enough for forty men. This makes me think the writers wanted Muhammad to seem like Jesus. They tried to take credit for Jesus’s life.

The book has many stories to show people converted to Islam on their own. But the stories are from other people. This makes them not seem true. It also makes me think the book has an agenda.

The book tries to make Muhammad look like a good and humble man. But history says he was not like that. I wonder if Muslims know the true story behind Muhammad.

After Jesus lived, his teachings and beliefs started to change. Christianity moved forward, but it went away from its start. Today, many people want to know and learn more about Jesus. They want to understand his true ideas. This will happen over time. The church will lead people to believe only what Jesus said. The beliefs of people will become more like each other. This is like history turning back. Christians were once hated by the Romans, but now the Romans became Christians. America changed from slavery to leadership. This change will happen again in Christianity. People will read Jesus' words as symbols, not as real statements. What happened after Jesus lived? The start of Christianity was Judaism. It had one God, a holy book, and many people. They had different beliefs.

I believe The Jungle shows that people are often greedy and selfish. They only think about themselves, not about others. The owners and managers of big factories want to make their companies and factories big. They do not care about anyone or anything that gets hurt by their work. The book says, "The line of the buildings stood clear-cut and black against the sky; here and there out of the mass rose the great chimneys, with the river of smoke streaming away to the end of the world." This shows that the owners do not care about the damage they cause.

The owners also do not care about their employees. They want to make or save money, no matter what. They make workers work long hours and may lay off many people suddenly. There were no laws to protect workers in the time The Jungle was set. The workers were treated like slaves. They were dependent on the owners' decisions. There were unions, but they often did not help the workers. The workers had no way to escape Packingtown. They were forced to live and work in bad conditions.

Many authors use different ways to make readers feel or think about important topics. F. Scott Fitzgerald uses many of these ways in The Great Gatsby. Sometimes, he pairs words that don't usually go together to make readers feel a certain way. For example, he does this with colors like gold, green, white-gray, and red-pink. In The Great Gatsby, Fitzgerald makes these colors mean something, then uses them to make readers feel about important things.

White-gray means uniformity. White is high class, gray is old and faded. Fitzgerald shows this in the beginning of the book. Daisy and Jordan always wear white. Even Nick wears white flannels to Gatsby's party. The only time people don't wear white is when Nick is seeing Gatsby's party. Fitzgerald also makes white and gray mean unimportant things. He uses these colors to describe plain or common things, like people and places. For example, the dog-seller is a gray old man.

Then, Fitzgerald uses these colors to show that Daisy is not important. He says she is dressed in white in a little white roadster. This makes her seem like something Gatsby wants. Fitzgerald uses this technique again with Daisy's fur collar and dress. This makes her seem uniform and not a real character.

San Diego County is good for growing many things. This is because the area has a good climate with much sun. Common crops include: tomatoes, oranges, lettuce, squash, broccoli, herbs, peaches, lemons, berries, honey, and peppers. Many people in the San Diego area like organic foods. These foods are grown without chemicals. Organic farms often have tours for people to visit and learn about farming.

Organic farming can be more difficult and costly than normal farming. It needs more work to keep pests and weeds away and fertilize the soil without chemicals. This can cause more losses than normal farming. Small organic farms also do not have the same efficiency as big farms. They do not use as many resources. Other good things for wildlife, like planting cover crops, can also cost more time and money.

The land in this example is next to the Cleveland National Forest. It is 160 acres. It has many types of plants and animals. Some are rare or in danger, like the Stephens' kangaroo rat and the mountain yellow-legged frog. The area was once home to Native Americans. Later, it was used for grazing and selling wood.

The landowner might use government programs to help with costs and protect wildlife. I looked at a farm in the same area to see what might be possible.

Culture is important in any negotiation. Culture can be defined by what it is not and what it means. It is not the same, not one thing. It is not the same in every place. Statements like "all Russians are stubborn" or "all Japanese are friendly" are not true. These are not good ways to understand a culture. It is better to understand how the culture affects the negotiation.

When you meet a new culture, you compare it to your own. You may learn about its history or its beliefs. You should not judge a culture. You should accept it and work within its rules, especially if you have less power in the negotiation. If you are in a new place, respect the traditions. This makes it easier to talk and make decisions.

Culture is not only about a country. Many companies in one country have their own way of doing things. For example, some companies want employees to work long hours, while others want them to work less. You can see the company's culture in how people dress, how they talk, and how they hire people. Even in one country, there can be many different company cultures.

Values are important to understand because they explain why a culture is the way it is. If a culture values saving face, a negotiator will not make someone look bad to succeed. If a culture values a hard bargain, a negotiator will not agree too fast. Understanding these things before the negotiation helps. But also, learn about the other person to make the negotiation better.

The Bible says, "The fool says, 'There is no God.'" This idea is in Psalm 14 and is used by St. Anselm to start his argument about God's existence. Thomas Aquinas also believes in God. We will compare their arguments to see whose is better. To do this, we will assume they both believe in the God of the Bible. This way, we can compare their arguments fairly.

St. Anselm says we can know God exists by thinking about it. He believes God's existence is in our minds. This is called faith. Thomas Aquinas, however, thinks we can prove God exists using reason and evidence. He has five arguments: change, causation, contingency, degrees of excellence, and harmony. In these arguments, he shows that God must exist because of logic. This makes his argument different from St. Anselm's. It doesn't need faith.

In the fifth or sixth century BCE, a prince became Buddha. He left the world and became enlightened. His teachings started Buddhism, the most important form being Theravada Buddhism. This religion is over 2500 years old. It looks different today than when Buddha lived. For example, in Sri Lanka, the annual water-cutting ceremony is done. Monks and people take part. This ceremony is not something Buddha taught. These changes happen from small things to big beliefs. The Theravada community has changed its beliefs over time. This is because of things outside and inside the community, both helpful and harmful.

We will use some special words in this talk. Internal is a force from people in the Buddhist community. External is a force from people not in the community. Hostile is a force that hurts the community. Benign is a force that does not want to hurt the community. These words will be used many times.

Now, let's learn about the basic beliefs of Theravada Buddhism. Buddhists find safety in the Triple Gem, which are the Buddha, the Dhamma, and the Sangha. The Dhamma is the Tripitaka, the three baskets of Buddhist books. The Sutta Pitaka has all the Suttas. The Vinaya Pitaka has rules for life. The Abhidhamma Pitaka has ideas about the nature of things. These ideas include things like Anatta, no soul; Dukkha, suffering; and Anicca, change. Understanding these makes it possible to end Sansara, the cycle of life and death. When someone becomes enlightened, desire, hatred, and delusion stop. The Vinaya Pitaka has rules for monks and laypeople. Monks have many rules, while laypeople have five rules. The most important belief in Buddhism is the Four Noble Truths. The first truth is that life is suffering. The second truth is that attachment causes suffering. The third truth is that suffering can be overcome.

The United States and Mexico were rivals for 57 years, from 1836 to 1893. The big fight was the Mexican-American War in 1846-1848. The United States won and got new land. There were many other fights, but they stopped before the First World War.

Many nations have this kind of rivalry with their neighbors. Nations near the United States had big problems with it. Mexico and Cuba had long, big problems with the United States. Other Latin American countries had good relations with the United States.

Religion caused many problems between the United States and Mexico. The United States did not like Catholicism and monarchy. This was like the Cold War, but about religion, not politics. The United States and Mexico did not trust each other because of old feelings from their former rulers.

There were 17 fights between Mexico and the United States. Most were about borders. Bandits and outlaws from the border were a big problem. Both countries used soldiers to stop this.

The rivalry stopped when Mexico became dependent on the United States. The United States then wanted to help Mexico with money, not take more land.

Fifteen years ago, I became suddenly sick. I did not know this would happen. I was a nurse. I chose this job because I wanted safety and security. I thought, "People always need help when they are sick."

Even though I dreamed of being a scientist or a journalist, I chose nursing. I was 46 years old and single. I had no money in the bank. Now, I am sick and cannot work.

I live on Social Security Disability. I have little money left. Every day is hard. I struggle to feel safe, happy, and confident.

Family and friends helped me. Without them, I could not have survived. When disaster happens, you need help.

Life has emergencies. Some are big. Some are small. Sometimes, people need to trust and help each other. We should ask for help, not make fallout shelters.

Conservatives talk about rugged individualism. But our forefathers helped each other. They did not make it alone.

Be prepared. I have a disaster kit. I have food, water, and heat sources. I know my neighbors.

Why do organisms change over time? Are there rules? In 1917, D'Arcy Thompson said that even now, scientists can't define simple organic shapes in math language. But now, math modeling helps. Our study uses math and experiments to understand how Prunum changes. We used X-rays to find important shell parts. We put these parts into a computer program. We made shells in the computer to see how they could change. This helps us understand big changes in Prunum.

A shell is like a tube that turns over time. These turns are called whorls. They go around a middle line called the columella. The biggest whorl is the last one. The spire is all the whorls except the last. The shell's tip is the apex and the bottom is the base. The animal comes out of the shell through an opening called the aperture.

We can see shells from different sides. The "usual" way is with the aperture facing us and the apex pointing up.

To count whorls, first see the shell from the top. Find the first line that separates whorls. Divide the shell and count from this line. Each whorl is about a quarter of a full turn.

A shell is a path of apertures over time and space. We can trace this path with math. Once we have a math recipe, we can change the recipe to see how the shell changes.

Indonesia has many problems with baby and mother health. The country is not meeting many goals for child and mother health. It is important to talk about these problems and make the health system stronger.

Many babies and mothers in Indonesia are dying. This must change. The country has made some good changes. More babies now have skilled workers at their birth. But many mothers are dying from bleeding. So, the changes have not been good enough.

Many children under five are not getting good care for diarrhea. The data about after-birth care is not complete, but the care is not good.

The number of babies born by caesarean is too low. Only 4% of all babies are born this way. In cities, 7% are born this way, and in rural areas, only 2% are. This shows that rich people get better health care than poor people.

Many poor people cannot get good health care. They cannot pay for it. This is a big problem.

The next step is to decide how to make the health care system better. Should we focus on specific programs or make the whole system stronger? Both ideas have good and bad sides. Programmatic approaches have clear, fast results. But they can cause problems too. They can make funding and workers go to one area and leave other areas without help. This can cause problems like duplication and too much paperwork.

Victorian novels often have many details and focus on the rich people of the time. Two books from this time, Oliver Twist and Wuthering Heights, are different. They use mystery and strange things to make the characters more interesting and show their feelings.

In Oliver Twist, the mystery often comes from dreams or dream-like states. These dreams show what Oliver is feeling and what he understands about the world. In Chapter 28, Oliver dreams about the shooting. He is not in control during this dream, and he feels pain and fear. This shows that Oliver cannot control his life or even try to save himself. The dream also shows that Oliver is feeling defeated, like Fagin has made him give up.

“The day passed off – day! There was no day; it was gone as soon as come – and night came on again; night so long, and yet so short; long in it’s dreadful silence and short in it’s fleeting ours.”

Two years ago, I worked in an after-school program helping elementary school students. I was good at English and reading. I helped a boy named Adrian who struggled with reading. He spoke perfect English, but had trouble with some letters. His mother did not speak English. I learned Spanish to help her. It turned out Adrian knew how to read but not the English alphabet. I hope he is doing better now.

I tell this story to talk about language barriers in schools, especially in California. Even children who speak English well can have reading problems. The solution is not simple. For Adrian, it was tutoring in English reading. But for children who speak little English, the problem is harder. We need to combine different ways to help. The dual language system is good. It helps all children, not just Spanish speakers. But we need more bilingual teachers or helpers.

Most people learn of something bigger than themselves when they are children. Some go to school to learn about it. Others go to a temple or search inside themselves. We may accept the beliefs of our parents, but some people reject them. We each have our own way to find our spirituality. We all search for light to guide us out of darkness.

My father liked cardinals, he said when I asked about his favorite bird. We sat on our porch one day, listening to rain. He was thin and his hair was sparse. He looked out into the rain, like he was searching and remembering. He did not look at me. I felt alone and afraid. I hugged him and sat close. We watched the rain together.

My father died in December. Chemo and radiation did not help him. He lived longer than doctors thought. But I did not want to watch him die. I did not watch him leave this life. I wanted to remember him by how he lived. I stayed in my bed for three days and waited for news.

No one called me.

The traditional "Gothic Novel" has been called "Old-New" by Ian Watt in The Rise of the Gothic Novel. The Gothic mode has had many names. Some people said it was good, and some said it was bad. The original Gothic Novel, The Castle of Otranto by Horace Walpole, used old and new ideas to create a new kind of story. Walpole used old theater ideas and new nature in his novel. He called it "A Gothic Story." This genre used old ideas from medieval theater, architecture, and traditions. In the past, the word "gothic" meant many different things. It was seen as old or simple in the face of modern society. The mix of old "Gothic" ideas and new novel ideas allowed the Gothic genre to live for a long time. It became both old and new for people who read it later.

One important idea in Gothic novels is chivalry. The original Gothic Novel, The Castle of Otranto, used this medieval idea. Chivalry was important to Gothic writers because it showed a brave and honorable knight. Walpole wrote The Castle of Otranto in a time of political trouble. He may have been sad about the future of society. In his story, he used chivalric concepts and manners to show an idealized past. This hinted at the future evolution of Gothic to Romantic. He showed this in the character Frederic. Before meeting him, he was described as a prince who had suffered and was affected by tragedy. He was also supposed to be killed by infidels. He was like a "gallant and courteous Knight."

Supply Chain Management
Supply Chain Management is the process of moving goods from start to finish. This includes raw materials, production, and delivery to customers. Keith Oliver, a consultant, created this term in 1982.

There are six important parts to a supply chain:
1. Production
2. Supply
3. Inventory
4. Location
5. Transportation
6. Information

Business managers use these parts to meet customer needs quickly and efficiently.

Production is the first step. It starts with knowing what customers want. Managers look at the market to find out. After understanding customer demand, managers decide what to produce and how much. They also decide where to produce and which plant is best. Then, they plan workloads and equipment maintenance.

Supply is the next key part. It involves making decisions about the best facilities and partnerships. A company may have many production divisions for one product. Each division has different equipment and workers. Managers choose the best division for each product process. They may also outsource work to other companies to reduce costs while keeping quality high.

Hitler is alive in Burma. Ellen Page, actor from Juno, stands alone on corner. She holds sign with message. Message says Hitler is alive.

Burma, also known as Myanmar, is Southeast Asian country. It is ruled by bad government. This government came to power in 1962. They use military force to rule.

In 2007, people in Burma protested against this bad government. Many people joined protests. Protests were led by monks. Protests became violent. Government fought monks with military. Many monks and people died.

Government killed many people. Some journalists were also killed. One journalist named Kenji Nagai was killed on September 27, 2007.

This is not new. Many governments have done bad things in the past. They want to stop people from saying bad things about them. They want to rule everything.

One example is in 1989. Many people protested in China. They wanted government to not be so bad. Many people died. Another example is in Rwanda. Many people were killed in 1990s. Many people were rounded up and killed because of their race.

People have always done bad things in history. They want to rule everything and stop people from protesting.

Duke Ellington's jazz music lasts long because of his ideas and how he leads his band. He is good with the piano but also writes music that shows what each band member can do best. He lets soloists play freely and makes sure their sound fits with the whole band. Ellington's music is unique and famous.

The Grove Music dictionary says Ellington uses voice as a musical instrument. Creole Love Call is an early example. This song has six parts. In the first part, the voice starts smooth and goes rough. The second part has a muted trumpet solo. The third part is a high clarinet solo with piano. The fourth part is like the first one, with brass and reed sections answering the voice. The fifth part is climactic, with reeds and brass playing high and syncopated. The last part goes back to the start, but the voice sounds like a growl.

In Hot and Bothered, Ellington uses his voice skills with "Bubber" Miley on muted trumpet and Baby Cox's scat singing. This creates a rich sound. It Don't Mean a Thing (If It Ain't Got That Swing) uses Joe "Tricky Sam" Nanton on muted trombone to make the melody interesting.

Ellington's way of using voice and instruments makes his music special.

She wanted something, but it eluded her. It began when she was 14, starting her teenage life. It continued at 17. She desired a person, not a thing. No boy interested her. Some tried to attract her, but none succeeded. She wondered why. Ideas came, but none explained it well enough. So, she lived, questioning her desires.

A day at home was usually peaceful. Her parents were good and calm. They rarely argued. Today, though, was different. She heard her mother cry from the kitchen. She rushed in. "Mom! What happened?" Her mother lay on the ground, in pain. She helped her mother to the car and drove to the hospital.

At the hospital, she carried her mother quickly. Doctors saw her. Her mother had fallen from a stool while fetching a vase.

This study shows that following a "Mediterranean Diet" (Med diet) reduces the risk of heart disease (CHD) and stroke. The Med diet is like the aMed diet but includes more plant foods, monounsaturated fat, and fish. It has less animal products and saturated fats. A little alcohol is okay.

Before, other studies said the Med diet helps with heart and blood vessel problems. This study is about stroke and stroke death. It followed 74,886 women for 20 years.

The study used self-reported food records 6 times. Most nurses stayed in the study. Medical records checked heart disease and stroke.

The study adjusted for things like age, smoking, body weight, and exercise. It used a method called Cox proportional-hazard modeling to see if the aMed diet score was linked to heart disease and stroke.

The study found that women who ate more like the Mediterranean diet had less heart disease and stroke. They also had less death from heart disease or stroke. Those who ate the most like the diet had about 30% less risk of heart disease and stroke compared to those who ate the least.

In 2007, the United States faced a big financial problem. Many people lost their jobs, the house market fell, and big companies were ruined. This problem still exists today. We need to know how this happened and how to stop it.

The financial problem started because leaders in politics made bad decisions. They forced banks and companies to give loans to people who had bad credit. Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac were forced to make these loans into special packages called CDOs and CDSs. When people could not pay back these loans, the banks lost money. This caused other problems in the economy.

This problem began in 1999 under the Clinton administration. The president wanted to stay in power, so he made it easier for people to get loans. This led to the financial problem seven years later. Steven Holmes, a writer for the New York Times, warned about this. He said that government-subsidized companies could face trouble in a slow economy.

Many reasons made the economy worse. One reason was the complicated way mortgages were made. There were adjustable-rate mortgages, mortgage-backed securities, and CDOs. These things made the economy link to the housing market. This made people and markets very risky.

The housing market crashed, and the banks that lent money lost a lot. The five biggest investment banks in the US had $4.1 trillion in mortgage debts in 2007. This was a big part of the US economy. Many banks had to sell cheaply, and some were closed or regulated. Fannie and Freddie, which had $5 trillion in mortgage debts, were taken over by the government.

Exposition is not good. It is when you tell readers things in simple words. This can make them bored or skip to the next part. You need to show, not tell. You need to let readers see things happen, not just tell them what happened.

In a story, exposition is when a character tells another character a lot of information. In a book, the author does this.

A bad example is when you read about a heroine meeting her husband and getting married, but it takes two pages with them only speaking a few lines. You need to show the husband's character, so readers care about him. You need to show how much he loved the heroine. You need to show how his love changed her life.

You need to give readers reasons to care about the story, not just tell them what happened. You need to make the story interesting.

I watched two news stories from Columbus, Ohio. The first was live on NBC 4. It reported a man named Shad Hostettler who stabbed his wife. He looked evil. The story was brief. The second story was about a shooting in Sharon Woods. An 18-year-old named Travis Buyers was hurt. There were no arrests. The SWAT team was investigating. This story was short. I think it was because the man was black. Minority victims get less attention than white victims. The next story was about a bullet hole in a Med-Flight helicopter. It was from a .22 caliber rifle. Crime-Stoppers offered a reward for the shooter. Another story was about rain and thunderstorms on Saturday. The forecast was for mid to low eighties. The story was short but they wanted to keep people watching. A story about a robbery at a Clime Road UDF was next. The robber was black and wore a hoodie. They spent more time describing him. Rene Rodriguez was mentioned. He was a Texas Drug-Kingpin and was sentenced to 300 months.

There is a special bond between brothers. This bond is very strong. It includes many feelings: love, pride, and sometimes cruelty. Brothers know each other very well. They see themselves when they look at their brother. The bond is strong, even in bad times. It shows good or bad feelings. These feelings have a big cost. To understand these feelings, we must look at the actions and results. In "The Scarlet Ibis", two brothers go on a journey. They have strong feelings. In the end, only one brother lives. The book shows these feelings through the main character, Doodle, and what he does. It also shows the narrator's thoughts. The main character feels pride. He wants to teach his brother many things. He wants them to do many fun activities. But Doodle has a weak heart. He can't do these things. The main character feels sad. He even thinks about hurting Doodle. But Doodle smiles at him. The main character feels happy. He loves Doodle. But he also feels sad. He has strong feelings.

The brain is a complicated system that changes information. People use different words to describe the brain as technology changes. In the past, the brain was compared to a wax tablet, then a sheet of papyrus, then a book, and now a computer. Remember, these ideas are not perfect and can lead to wrong answers.
Information starts with input from the senses. This turns physical things like touch, heat, sound, or light into signals. The brain uses two types of processing, bottom-up and top-down. Bottom-up processing puts together simple information to decide what you see, like a black box. Top-down processing helps you understand what you see, like a black box instead of a hole. Your brain processes many things at once, but attention decides what is important. Memory stores information for a while. There are many kinds of memory, like sensory, working, and long-term. Working memory uses short electrical signals. Long-term memory uses proteins to keep information. There are many ways to organize knowledge in the brain. One way is the semantic network model. This model has nodes for concepts linked by their relations, like "chair" linked to "table" and "wooden."

Aldous Huxley's Brave New World warns about technology and capitalism. It shows a society where people care more about being happy than being individuals. They are controlled by a leader called the World Controller. The story uses ideas from Marxism to show problems with this society. People are not free and do not know about the true power of different social classes. They are made to want to buy and spend things. The World Controller controls this. The lower classes do not know they are being controlled. The people do not have real emotions or love. They only care about their appearance and their place in society. This shows that technology and capitalism can take away a person's freedom and real feelings.

I have been a student at University Park for two and a half years, or four and a half semesters. Many students, including me, find it hard to get around campus. My freshman year, I lived in East Halls, far from the center of campus. Walking from there to classes could take 25 minutes, especially in bad weather, which is common in State College. In the past, East Halls was separate from the rest of the school by empty land. Now, that space has been filled with sports fields, new buildings, and apartments. As campus grows, moving from one place to another gets harder. What is the best solution? A bicycle is a good option for college students. But, students need to use them, and the campus must be designed for bicycle travel.

I talked to a friend who started riding his bike again after a long break. He said, “Bikes are great. It’s the only easy way to get around.” Riding a bike is good for you and fast. A bowl of oatmeal and some exercise can take you 30 miles or more. I live off campus, far from the center like some dorms. This year, I decided to buy a bike. It saves me time. It takes 5 minutes to ride to Thomas building, where I have class. Pollock Road is the fastest way to get there, but it can be hard to ride. Walking is also an option, but I’m too busy to walk. If I didn’t have my bike, walking would be my only way to get to class. Walking would take an extra 30-40 minutes each day, or 2.5 hours a week. This is too much time to spare.

In pursuing an education in social work, I intend to follow a career path with the Division of Family and Children Services to help children who have been abused or neglected; and to provide support for troubled families. Values that I can provide to the social work field include the following: service, respect, ethical nature, commitment to help improve relationships between others and to improve myself professionally to remain competent in my field. These core values are not just important to social workers; they are important to me personally. 

	I have always wanted to help others, but I was unsure of the career path that I wanted to follow. Throughout my years in high school and college, I saw many individuals flee from their problems in denial and a few used coping mechanisms that were less than ideal. Because of situations that I have witnessed, I chose to pursue a Bachelor’s degree in Psychology. Still unsure of a career path, I decided to take a break once I graduated from Piedmont College in 2009. One day that summer, I visited a friend who introduced me to a sixteen year-old boy sitting nervously on her couch. She explained to me why he was visiting: to escape his abusive parents. The next day, I learned that he had called the police to his parent’s residence. To see if I could help in any way, I drove over to his parents’ house. Once there, I privately explained my concerns to the police and told them I had just graduated with a degree in Psychology from Piedmont College. The police requested that I talk to the parents since there was nothing that the law could do for the teenager. When I questioned the parents about the situation, they seemed nervous and used excuses to describe their son’s “manipulative” behavior for involving outside sources to resolve “simple” disputes. After this particular experience, I began to seriously consider a career in social work to help children with “simple” disputes among family members.

	Another value that is important for the field of social work is social justice. As a society, we claim that the individual is important and we mourn those that we have lost. The concept of the “individual” that society holds is more a follower of archaic traditions than actual uniqueness. So, if society mourns lost individuals, then why do we strive to be similar to “everyone else?” I am an individual and do not enjoy placing limitations on myself to be similar to others. Throughout my years at high school and college, I protested against social injustice whenever I could: coloring my hair unnatural colors, wearing clothing that fit my personality, piercing my ears past the traditional set, declaring my involvement with GSBA (Gay Straight Bisexual Alliance), fighting against both racism and discrimination whenever I witnessed it, etc. I believe in social justice and I will continue to protest against social injustice.

The following paper addresses the Biological and Sociocultural models in relation to the disorder insomnia. The biological model focuses on genetic information that is inherited as well as medical aspects of health. The Sociocultural models look at environmental relationships and their applications to race, ethnicity, demographics, and socioeconomic status. The following review of insomnia looks at these models and explains each piece of research chosen to relate to and to better explain the models. The explanations of the research and their findings are then critiqued to mention their specific strengths and weaknesses.

A sleep disorder can be characterized as a primary sleep disorder, a sleep disorder related to another mental disorder, or a sleep disorder related to other issues. The Primary sleep disorders are Dyssonmias or Parasomnias while sleep disorders related to another mental disorder are related to an Axis I or Axis II disorder. Other categories of sleep disorders can be due to medical complications or the intake of a substance. The Dyssomnias are: Primary Insomnia, Primary Hypersomnia, Narcolepsy, Breathing- Related Sleep Disorder, Circadian Rhythm Sleep Disorder, and Dyssomnia Not Otherwise Specified (NOS). While Primary Insomnia is a complication in adequate or maintained sleep, Primary Hypersomnia is a difficulty in staying awake, both for at least a one month period of time. Narcolepsy involves cataplexy and/ or automatic REM. While Dyssonmias focus on initiating and remaining asleep, the Parasomnias are sleep disorders associated with behavioral abnormalities and/ or physiological occurrences. Parasomnias are Nightmare Disorder, Sleep Terror Disorder, Sleepwalking Disorder, and Parasomnias Not Otherwise Specified. The sleep disorders related to another mental disorder involve sleep difficulties due to Axis I (Clinical Disorders) or Axis II (Personality Disorders or Mental Retardation). The following review focuses on insomnia, and somewhat on primary sleep disorders in general in relation to the biological and sociocultural models.

	 The biological model of sleep disorders focuses on genes, heritable factors, and physiologically acquired aspect of sleep disorders. Neurons in the hypothalamus containing orexin are responsible for the regulation of sleep and wakefulness. This study experimented with mice and found that there are phenotypic GABAB receptors on the orexin neurons which are specifically responsible for sleep/ wake states. The activation of the GABAA receptor induces responses that promote sleep. If it is inhibited from firing, this can cause reduced anxiety and induce sleep. The GABAB agonist (baclofen) increased sleep time (Matsuki et al., 2009). Such results imply that the animal models of mice can be generalized to studies in humans. This shows that there is a genetic and environmental basis for the physical GABAB receptor in humans. A problem or absence with this receptor could alter the ability of one to have adequate sleep without medication. The sociocultural implication of this study is that if the phenotype was inherited, this could regulate sleep, and an alteration of the receptor would naturally disturb sleep for an individual. This would negatively impact aspects of life such as school, career, and every day events that involve monotonous tasks and focus.

This paper covers three areas of Central Auditory Processing Disorder (CAPD). First, a brief definition of the disorder is provided. Next, diagnosis is explained, with common characteristics, or “red flags”. Finally, the paper concludes with ways that a teacher in a mainstreamed classroom environment can assist a student with CAPD.

	Central Auditory Processing Disorder (CAPD), or Auditory Processing Disorder (APD) “refers to the efficiency and effectiveness by which the central nervous system (CNS) utilizes auditory information. Narrowly defined, (C)AP refers to the perceptual processing of auditory information in the CNS and the neurobiologic activity that underlies that processing and gives rise to electrophysiologic auditory potentials” (American Speech-Language-Hearing Association, 2005), meaning it is a disorder wherein the central nervous system (i.e. the brain) cannot properly process things that are heard. People with CAPD can hear normally, and are therefore not considered “hearing impaired”; rather, the area of the brain that translates what we hear, separating words or differentiating conversation from background noise does not function as it typically should. 

	The earliest mention of the disorder that became CAPD is from the mid-1950s, called “auditory imperception” (American Speech-Language-Hearing Association, 2005) when researchers were evaluating children with communicative disorders. The Italian research team of Bocca, Calearo, and Cassinari began developing tests for these children in 1954; in 1961, Kimura “introduced dichotic testing and formulated a model to explain the physiology of the CANS underlying dichotic perception” (American Speech-Language-Hearing Association, 2005). A national conference was held in 1977 that stimulated research on children with CAPD. 

	CAPD manifests itself in multiple ways: the person suffering may not be able to localize or hear sound in space; may have difficulty discriminating between two or more “acoustic events” (sound occurrences); may not be able to recognize sound patterns; may not be able to differentiate changes in speech (like detecting sarcasm based on change of voice); one sound may be blocked by a subsequent sound; may not have the ability to synthesize sound clues (that is, interpret in a meaningful way that they can then act upon); and may not be able to determine the sequence in which auditory information is presented (Ferre).

	In order to diagnose CAPD, the patient must be screened with “systematic observation of listening behavior and/or performance on tests of auditory function”, which may be conducted by “audiologists, SLPs, psychologists, and others using a variety of measures that evaluate auditory-related skills” (American Speech-Language-Hearing Association, 2005). This may include questionnaires and surveys, observation of auditory behaviors, including how the patient responds to certain stimuli. There is, at this time, no one tool or test that is used consistently to a high rate of diagnostic success, and there is no known cause for the disorder. Many tests used present the patient with multiple, simultaneous auditory stimuli and then ask for them to differentiate certain items, like a series of words or numbers. More advanced tests include recording acoustic signals within the ear and measuring the responses to the signals.

The play Twelfth Night seems to say that although disguise is in fact useful in perpetrating long bouts of deception, in the end a person must reject that newly formed guise, or else risk losing themselves forever in the process. A big problem with ending a deception, however, is that one may find themselves alienated in the process. Therefore, in the end, one must decide between one’s own self preservation, or the preservation of relationships with those around them. For although some will respond neutrally to discovering that they’ve been tricked, still others will not take the deception so lightly, and will be likely be offended by the whole charade.
The topic of deception in gender role reversal is especially problematic, because it brings up many side issues, perhaps the most important one being, why? Why does the subject feel the need to shirk their own identity and take up a disguise in the form of the opposite gender? In Viola’s case, it is obviously a form of self protection.: “I’ll bring you to a captain in this town/ Where lie my maiden weeds, by whose gentle help/ I was preserved to serve this noble count…” (5.1.247-249)
Having newly arrived in a foreign land, Viola feels it necessary to pretend to be a man to protect herself from would be attackers. Viola’s plan works, but it also alienates her from the women around her, cutting her off from an important support system. To make matters worse, she is apparently so convincing at appearing to be a man that Olivia confuses her with Sebastian, and in effect falls in love with her. “Whither, my lord? Cesario, husband, stay.” (5.1.138) On top of that, she also has to deal with suppressed romantic desires between her and Orsino: “Boy, thou hast said to me a thousand times/ Thou never shouldst love woman like to me.” (5.1. 260-261)
Although this may be a somewhat progressive attitude, to the modern reader, Twelfth Night may be seen as an illustration of how deception may help facilitate the unveiling of suppressed emotions, especially in the cases of Olivia and Orsino. Certain passages seem to hint that the aforesaid characters may have unexpressed subconscious desires that the appearance of Viola/Cesario forces them to deal with. For instance, is Olivia attracted to Cesario because Cesario appears to be a man, or does Olivia really secretly harbor feelings for women? One would argue that this is probably not the case, because Shakespeare’s character Olivia seems more likely to be parodying those people of his time period who judge others only upon their looks. 
This is evidenced by the ease with which Olivia switches her romantic ardors from Cesario to Sebastian, and begins to regard Cesario/Viola as family rather than a love interest: “A sister, you are she.” (5.1.315)

German colonial rule has been noted by various observers for its brutality, notably with respect to the genocide of the Ovaherero and Nama in German South West Africa. Of course nothing so broad as an entire colonial empire can be accounted for by such a simple description. The German colonial empire was as varied in policies and ruling style as it was in geography. Educational provision across the colonies was similarly diverse. When the British took over German East Africa (Tanganyika) in 1919, they found a large population of educated and literate Africans. German educational efforts in Kamerun and other colonies were also praised by contemporary authors. 
The situation in South West Africa (present-day Namibia) presented a stark contrast.  Unlike in East Africa, where the government established state schools and played a prominent role in the education of the natives, in South West Africa the task of native education was left almost entirely to missionary societies that received limited government support. The government did however invest significant resources towards the education of Europeans in the colony, establishing s system of state schools as well as more heavily supporting and regulating missionary schools. These educational policies had longstanding effects on South West Africa, even after German rule. While other German colonies boasted significant numbers of literate and educated Africans, in South West Africa “the overwhelming majority of the population remained untouched, uneducated, and illiterate.” Various social, political, and economic factors led to the divergent experience of South West Africa. This paper seeks to expand the discussion by identifying these factors and paying particular attention to new research on the attitudes of settlers and colonial authorities to native Africans.
There is a wealth of literature dealing with education in the German colonial empire specifically. Most of these sources are in German and were written in the early twentieth century, during or shortly after the period of German colonial rule. The aim of early works was primarily to describe the features of educational systems in these colonies. Later writings in English expanded the discourse through comparative studies of education in the various German colonies and more detailed analyses of specific aspects of education. These studies illustrated significant differences in the educational systems of different colonies. The most prominent work to explicitly address the topic of this paper is Cohen’s study of education in South West Africa and East Africa. Cohen compares the educational systems of the two colonies and discusses the factors that account for the differences between them. According to Cohen, the large settler population of South West Africa explains many of the distinguishing aspects of the colony’s educational system.
Compared to Germany’s other colonial possessions, South West Africa had a moderately temperate climate, although much of the territory is covered by arid desert. The European population of South West Africa reflected the relatively hospitable conditions. By 1913 nearly 15,000 whites lived in South West Africa, while only 5,336 lived in the colony with the next largest settler population, East Africa.

‎	‏The classification of Popular Music has grown over the past‭ ‬100‭ ‬years to include so many genres that it is difficult to definitively list them all. Complicating matters,‭ ‬most if not all genres—rap,‭ ‬rock,‭ ‬country,‭ ‬jazz,‭ ‬folk,‭ ‬just to name a few—have spawned multiple sub and sub-sub genres within their domain.  Arguably the sub-genre of Heavy Metal rock has become one of the most diverse and expressive genres of all popular music in the past‭ ‬40‭ ‬years. It is expressive because it displays a wide range of emotions,‭ ‬although they tend to lean toward the darker side of the spectrum. It is diverse in that quite soon after the beginnings of the genre,‭ ‬people started to realize that it had real flexibility and started to take advantage of it to create their own sub-genre,‭ ‬which then was followed by sub-sub-genres,‭ ‬and the chain continues until today. 

Today we have reached a point in the heavy metal movement where there are so many niches of groups that it is hard to determine what exactly heavy metal is. It has grown to incorporate so many themes from other genres,‭ ‬but like everything else,‭ ‬it spawned from somewhere. In order to properly understand the metal music that exists everywhere today,‭ ‬one must first understand what the metal movement is,‭ ‬and why it’s a movement rather than just a genre.

‎	‏Metal is,‭ ‬in many ways,‭ ‬a movement defined by darkness. Metal can be considered a‭ “‬music of more‭”—‬more bass,‭ ‬more volume,‭ ‬more violence,‭ ‬more theatricality. Less primitivism,‭ ‬more chops‭; ‬people in metal bands really know how to play their instrument,‭ ‬and it comes through in the music. Metal is also—although it may not come as a surprise—a movement that is heavily drug induced. There was a psychedelic drug boom in the mid-70‭’‬s that led to people getting crazier,‭ ‬leading to them to make crazy,‭ ‬other-worldly records,‭ ‬using the drugs as a scapegoat for their creation. It possesses many dark,‭ ‬visceral qualities,‭ ‬which was very new to the music scene because a large amount of popular music had qualities that weren’t true to the darker side of the emotional spectrum. Also,‭ ‬later generations of metal have taken some of their influence from the dark,‭ ‬visceral qualities that were so present in the Romantic Era. Lyrics such as the following express the darkness that is such a staple of the movement:‭ (‬Byrne‭)‬


	
These lyrics from Helter Skelter display the darker side of the Beatles. It exhibits an up and down,‭ ‬supposedly that of drugs. This song is considered by some to be one of the first Heavy Metal songs. It was a response to a Rolling Stones song that was also on the heavier,‭ ‬darker side. The Beatles wanted to prove that they could be just as heavy as the Stones,‭ ‬so they put that song on‭ ‬The White Album.

A few decades before the Surrealist artists began painting their dreamlike works, the artist Henri Rousseau was carefully crafting his own dreams, literally and figuratively. The Dream, a 1910 painting by the famous Post-Impressionist artist, represents not only a woman in awe at the wonders of the land she visits within a dream, but also Rousseau’s own personal dreams and goals as a painter. Since beginning his work, he dreamed of recognition, acceptance, and praise by other artists and art lovers, and found that he was faced with a difficult internal dilemma to achieve this aspiration. The Dream is Henri Rousseau’s work that best reflects his career-long internal struggle: to either conform to or mimic certain styles of painting in order to be accepted by the critical art world he so adored, or to allow himself to be creatively independent and unique, leaving his own path as he went.
Before one can analyze The Dream through this perspective, one must first be somewhat familiar with Rousseau’s biographical story. Henri Rousseau was born on May 21, 1844, in the town of Laval in northwest France. His father was a tinsmith and hardware dealer who “enjoyed bourgeois prosperity” (Shattuck 47). Growing up, he received no formal training in the arts; instead, he was employed until the age of forty working for France as a gabelou, or employee of the municipal toll service, although he received the misnomer sobriquet of douanier, a customs inspector (Shattuck 46). The death of his first wife, Clémence, which followed the deaths of eight infant children, left Rousseau with only one child, a daughter named Julia, and immense grief (Shattuck 49). He therefore hoped to take refuge in a new life and pursued painting to offer him comfort and fresh beginnings. Unlike contemporary colleagues of Rousseau who sentimentalize and romanticize the peasant in painting, he is essentially a folk painter and has the hopes and dreams of the average member of his class.
Rousseau’s obsession with being accepted by the art world is somewhat understandable when evaluated in context: as discussed, he was not only uneducated in the ways of formal painting and began his career at a much older age, but he was producing works at the same time as many other talented and better-known modern artists. Though working for many years already, Rousseau did not begin to receive proper recognition for his art until around the same time that Matisse had begun crafting a reputation as an artist. In the book Modern French Painters, author Jan Gordon asserts that the two, while technically competitors in the art arena, were different not only in style and subject matter but also their reasons for painting in the first place: “Matisse was a painter who conceived a terror of painting in a trite way, while Rousseau’s desire was to paint a picture so conventional that he would be admitted to the Artiste Français” (92).

Many a great thinker has postulated an intimate connection between ethics and aesthetics, between truth and beauty. I believe that at a fundamental level there is a reason for this. As John Keats says in “Ode on a Grecian Urn”, “Beauty is truth, truth beauty- That is all / Ye know on earth, and all ye need to know.” Much of what we know in life is learned via education or experience. However, we seem to appreciate ethics and aesthetics, as Keats implies, without being taught in these expected ways. Both ethics and aesthetics are an attempt to describe rather then prescribe. Our studies of morality and beauty are, for the most part, attempts to explain why a piece of art or literature is beautiful, or why an action is moral, rather than a set of rules for judging, or creating, good art or moral behavior. 
	More to the point, criticism of art or morals is never able to fully capture the essence of what is good or what is beautiful. A conversation about the worth of da Vinci's Mona Lisa, for example, may center around concepts like foreground, background, contrast, or cultural context, but in the end, these do not describe why it is good art. Rather, when one is asked about a favorite work of art or literature it is common to hear a phrase similar to, “There's just something about it” preceding a more complex or critical explanation. I believe that both art and morals can never be completely reduced to a description of their qualities. As Flannery O'Connor says, “A story is a way to say something that can't be said any other way . . . you tell a story because a statement would be inadequate.” No matter how completely we describe the properties of a work of literature, there is something transcendent which is still left. I believe that ethics has this same property. As Wittgenstein says, “It is clear that ethics cannot be expressed. / Ethics is transcendental. / . I suggest that it is this “something”, this je ne sais quoi, which is art and morality's most powerful attribute, and that this transcendental nature of both ethics and aesthetics provides a connection point between them.
	I believe that morality and art are so closely related because we experience both of them most powerfully at a noumenally, to use a Kantian term. They impact us at a level that can be experienced, but not fully explained. This link is even stronger when it comes to the art of literature. As McKean says, “What most distinguishes literature from the other arts, what is, in truth, unique about the art, is its moral quality. It may be that moral standards are inappropriate to other arts, music, for instance, but they seem to be as relevant to literature as they are to life itself. Living necessarily involves values. . . . Literature is important to us precisely because of the values we find there” .

The Germany of today is considered a strong force, a united country with its own blend of culture from within the shadows of the alps in München, all the way to Baltic sea city of Kiel.  The same culture can be felt from Köln on the river Rhine, through the centre of Germany to the Saxon city of Dresden located on the Elbe. With such a unique culture, it shouldn't be surprising that Germany as we now know it comes from several different sources, and tribes. 

Germania is the ancestral land of the Germans. The origins of the name are highly disputed among scholars and historians. Tacitus claimed that the name came from a Germanic Tribe known then as Tungrians, and that they had previously been known as Germans before they crossed the Rhine and battled the Gaulish forces (Tacitus, 98.) Julius Caesar first used the word “Germanus” in his commentary on the Gallic Wars where he put down the Gauls and battled with Germanic tribes which crossed the Rhine often under mischievous premisses. He took this word from The Gauls themselves, and used it to distinguish between those which he had conquered (The Gauls) and those which he had not. While the origin is uncertain, some believe it referred to a neighbor in the Gaulish language. In the first chapter, of his first book on these wars, Julius Caesar notes: “Germans, who dwell beyond the Rhine, with whom they (The Gauls) are continually waging war.....They contend with the Germans in almost daily battles.” (Julius Caesar, 50-40 BC) Others claim the meaning comes from the spear that they used in warfare, known as a ger (O.E.D, 2010), or perhaps from the Old Irish word garim meaning “to shout”, which indicated the Germans were loud, or noisy. (Names of Germany) 

 The early Roman historian Tacitus recorded in his AD 98 writing “De Origine et situ Germanorum”, which told of the origins of the Germans, that “I should regard (The Germans) as aboriginal, and not mixed at all with other races through immigration or intercourse. For, in former times it was not by land but on shipboard that those who sought to emigrate would arrive.......Who would leave Asia, or Africa, for Italy for Germany, with its wild country, its inclement skies, its sullen manners and aspect, unless indeed it were his home?(SIC)” (Tacitus, 98) 

And who would leave Rome for Germania? Certainly not the Romans, not yet at least. They would send out their conquests into the lands of Germania for goods, and lead the occasional land campaign but in the end they mostly returned back home to their sprawling empire. So as the Germanic tribes began appearing in the middle of the first century, they lived on the borders of the Roman Empire and traded their goods taken from the land, and their skills by serving within the ranks of the Roman army, (Ozment, 2005 pg. 17.)

Downwards I stared, mind blankly comprehending the view in front of me.  Unemotionally, silently, with a practiced awareness that studied but refused to relate the object of study to any abstract understanding my mind analyzed the picture before my eyes.  Thoughts slipped into my mind and slipped out again almost faster than they appeared.  So smoothly and so cleanly my consciousness worked that it seemed I had no real thoughts of my own, just an active and liquid experience of what I was looking at. 
Once, on advice from an artist I worked with, I purchased an art instruction book called The New Drawing on the Right Side of the Brain.   I had wanted to learn how to draw ever since I was six years old and this book teaches everything from understanding what a pencil is to processes the brain uses to interpret lines.  One technique the book teaches is to place a square frame around any picture the artist wishes to study.  Thus transforming an overwhelmingly detailed picture, for instance a bowl of fruit sitting on a table located in a kitchen that is connected to a dining room, into an easily grasped picture, that bowl of fruit sitting on a simple plane.   
At the time, staring down at the bowl in front of me I could not mentally project that artist’s frame.  I was so overwhelmed, so awed that I could only stand and gaze in wonderment.  Picasso went through his blue phase, Monet loved greenery, Italian Renaissance masters displayed a rainbow of colors. If I had any pretensions of casting my perspective as worthy of the title Artistic then before me were the beginnings of my picture, the start of my story, Work in Brown.  
Fingertips alighted on my chosen implement of artistry, muscles tightened and relaxed as my hand passed through space, my mind’s will given shape and form in what could have been the most creative moment of my life.  Water swirled, serene and smooth, crystal clear and clean.  Flakes of matter broke away from the whole and were carried away to nothingness.  Muscles tightening, jerking and spasming a little more quickly and anxious the second time, my hand smacked the handle of the toilet again.  The offensive brown package refused to move, stuck like a slug on the bottom of the toilet.  
Mop gripped loosely in hand, feet set a foot apart, green tie knotted uncomfortably around my throat, I frowned slightly as I stared at the rude bundle of processed animal and plant matter someone had left as a message for the suckers who cleaned the bathrooms at Rite Aid.  A few flushes more, a few more tranquil introspective moments to myself, then my hand moved towards the wall to my right, gripped the sheet at the end of the toilet paper, and began mummifying itself until it resembled an oven mitt.   Standing up straight, then bending at the waist, my hand dipped slowly into the bowl, like a mother going into an oven for the Thanksgiving turkey….

Teenagers are dying behind the wheel.  Several factors come together to create this deadly vector of statistics for the youngest American drivers.  The National Institutes of Health explain that one facet of the problem is that the teen brain is literally not ready for the hazards of driving. Simple inexperience also lies at the heart of the problem. This inexperience not only causes more fatal accidents, but also a higher rate of vehicle rollover, speeding, and driving off the road.  
Teens also fare far worse when they travel with their peers—which anyone with an iota of sense knows they do on a regular basis.  The Southern California Injury Prevention Research Center conducted a study that showed the following correlation: between the age of the passenger and the number of traffic accidents occurring.
	California and other states have attempted to increase the safety of teen drivers by requiring temporary provisional licenses that limit the hours that teens may drive and prohibit other minors as passengers.
	But provisional driver’s licenses are, in my opinion, stopgap measures.  The real issue is that—as a group—the youngest drivers are, by all statistical markers, simply not able to adequately handle the risks and responsibilities.  Psychologist Marvin Zuckerman believes even 18 is too young for a regular driver’s license.  USA Today reports that Zuckerman has performed research suggesting a common desire among those under the age of 19-20 to take risks for the sheer thrill of the sensation.  It makes sense then, to delay driving at least until the tendency to thrill-seek has begun to level out.  If we continue to issue driver’s licenses to young teens, we will not only continue to see deadly accidents happening, but the death toll is likely to reach staggering proportions in the next few years.  By 2010, the Baby-Boomer’s babies will be eligible to drive and millions of new teen drivers will ready to hit the road.  
Legislation dealing with this issue would be reasonably straightforward.  Schools could continue to provide driver’s education classes to begin the learning process for future drivers, but no one under the age of 18 could operate a motor vehicle.  A provisional permit could still be issued prior to granting a full driver’s license, and a certain number of practical driver’s training hours would still be required as well.  The specific number of hours required could be based on the number of hours already required by the majority of states (in California, for example, that number is currently 6 hours of behind-the-wheel training and 50 hours of practice with an adult.)  Because the deadly statistics for teen drivers come from a cross-section of all states, uniform, national legislation on this issue would be a reasonable—and I believe effective—means of protecting teens across the nation. 
The legislation I suggest is by no means a novel idea.

In looking through the Library of Congress’s library of early Edison films, I decided to view all of the trick films, of which there were fifteen from 1895 to 1901. These films generally take advantage of creative editing to produce illusions. My film study generally focused on describing the poetics for the majority of trick films and examining the evolutionary outlier characteristics present in a few of the later films. Largely, the trick film at the turn of the century is set-bound, composed within a frontal proscenium, features no camera movement, uses long and medium shots, and adheres to the strict one shot = one film methodology. However, there are some films at the beginning of the twentieth century that dare to break these guidelines by introducing aspects such as multiple shots.
One of the most noticeable aspects that the trick films share in common is their filming in an interior set within the frame of a frontal proscenium. The camera does not move from its proscenium position to follow figures or objects. This composition was very common in early films, and drew its root from the theatre and, for trick films, vaudeville and magic acts. One of the limitations inherent in the use of the stage is that figures in trick films generally only move side-to-side, and do not walk towards or away from the camera. Take, for example, the action in the film Uncle Josh in a Spooky Hotel (1900). The actors enter from the right side and move back and forth along the horizontal axis. Even as they go out of the frame, the camera does not follow them.
The frontal proscenium style of composition also means that shots tend to be long shots and, more rarely, medium shots. Close-up shots are never used in any of the trick films from the Edison catalog.
